@* T[] array (BENCH n°36, decision 117): a `int[]` indexed by a reactive index. `items` is an array literal
   [10, 20, 30] -- a T[] maps to the SAME JS array a List<T> does (read-only: indexing, .Length, iteration).
   `i` is a signal, and #next advances it (mod the length), so @items[i] steps through the array. #value goes
   "10" -> "20" -> "30" -> "10", exactly as Blazor indexes the same C# array. items is read by @items[i] but
   never mutated -> a plain array; i is read AND assigned -> a signal. (An array is READ-ONLY here; a mutable
   collection is a List<T>, whose element write bumps the reactive version.) *@

<p>Item: <span id="value">@items[i]</span></p>

<button id="next" @onclick="Next">next</button>

@code {
    private int[] items = new int[] { 10, 20, 30 };
    private int i = 0;

    private void Next()
    {
        i = (i + 1) % items.Length;
    }
}
